@creikey 
According to ancient yogic tradition, SR is the jnana yoga path, which is the understanding based path to enlightenment. They say people who can walk the jnana yoga path to enlightenment are exceedingly rare. In contrast, Jamie thinks that SR is possible for everyone. Take your pick. Personally I have no idea. Psychedelics may also open possibilities for many individuals because they can facilitate incredible change in mental states. 
Suppose SR isn't possible for you for whatever reason. If you don't experience SR living life is your only option. Even if you *do* experience SR that is still your only option. If you see SR as escape, then what you are pursuing does not exist. Practically speaking, never trying to pursue SR may be the best way to approach suffering for most people. After all, many people want SR because they don't want to live their own life, but SR doesn't let you escape your own life. Specifically for you Creikey, since you are so convinced that SR isn't possible for yourself, I think you should either be true to that statement and completely give up or double down on self-inquiry 100%. Pursuing SR while believing that it isn't possible for yourself probably isn't a good use of your time (although you may prove me wrong, SR may be possible for your mind whether or not you believe it is).

